bib_record.title: Electromagnetic dipole strength of 136Ba below the neutron separation energy

free_txt: Part of the measurement performed
at ELBE facility in Rossendorf
Part of the measurement performed
at the HIgS facility at TUNL
At ELBE four 100% high-purity Germanium (HPGe)
detectors were used. Two were positioned at 90deg and
two at 127deg relative to the beam axis. Each
detector was surrounded by an escape suppression
shield of bismuth germanate (BGO) which works as a
veto detector, increasing the ratio of full energy
events relative to all events. Lead collimators, each
10-cm thick, were placed in front of the detectors.
At HIgS four 60% HPGe detectors were placed
around the  target position at a polar angle of 90deg.
Two of them were placed in the horizontal plane,
and the other two were placed in the vertical plane
No information on source of uncertainties
Part of the measurement performed
at ELBE facility in Rossendorf
Part of the measurement performed
at the HIgS facility at TUNL
The target itself was a compound
of BaCO3 with a total mass of 2381.89 mg and an
enrichment of 93% in 136Ba. The BaCO3 was mixed with
11B for monitoring purposes. The amount of 11B in the
target was 318.1 mg.
At ELBE bremsstrahlung was produced by electrons
with energies up to 20 MeV hitting a thin niobium foil
In this experiment electron energies of 7.0 and
11.4 MeV were used.
